entry.title: DOM: Reorder Observable completion events
entry.content:
This CL "fixes" Observable unsubscription/teardown timing. As a matter

of accidental historical precedent, Observables in JavaScript (but not

in other languages) had implemented the "rule" that upon

Subscriber#error() or Subscriber#complete(), the subscriber would:

1. First, invoke the appropriate Observer callback, if provided (i.e.,

complete() or error() callback).

2. Signal abort Subscriber#signal, which invokes any teardowns and also

fires the `abort` event at the signal.



However, after dom@chromium.org discussed this more with

ben@benlesh.com, we came to the conclusion that the principle of "as

soon as you know you will teardown, you MUST close the subscription and

any upstream subscriptions" should be adhered. This means the above

steps must be inverted. This is a small-in-size but medium-in-impact

design change for the Observable concept, and led to a blog post [1] and

an announcement [2] that the RxJS library intends to change its

historical ordering of these events.



This CL:

1. Inverts the order of the aforementioned steps in the Blink

implementation.

2. Improves some tests that assert this new ordering.

3. Simplifies the takeUntil() operator in general.



The Observable spec will be updated alongside this commit:

https://github.com/WICG/observable/pull/120.



[1]: https://benlesh.com/posts/observables-are-broken-and-so-is-javascript/

[2]: https://github.com/ReactiveX/rxjs/issues/7443

entry.title: Reland "[Default Nav Transition] Implement AnimationManager"
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit 249bf160e0b67010d1ddbd074ecb2df75dfa859b



Revert reason: https://issues.chromium.org/issues/326151124#comment1

Fix: the NavigationQueueing requires full SiteIsolation enabled [1].

On Android, `AreAllSitesIsolatedForTesting()` returns false without

--site-per-process [2].



However we want to avoid the entire CL being reverted for an offending

test. In this CL we simply disable this test and will re-enable it in

a different CL. It's safe to do because neither NavigationQueueing

nor DefaultNavTransition are shipped yet.



The new changes are in diff PS1..onward.



[1]: https://crsrc.org/c/content/browser/navigation_browsertest.cc;drc=9d7d5775ef19f356931a2418cc4c1bb965173200;l=6037

[2]: https://crsrc.org/c/content/public/browser/site_isolation_policy.cc;drc=f4a00cc248dd2dc8ec8759fb51620d47b5114090;l=98



Original change's description:

> [Default Nav Transition] Implement AnimationManager

>

> Full impl of the AnimationManager interface for mainframe cross-doc

> navigations only. Only the transformational animations are included

> (i.e., layer moving animations). Does not include scrim or cross-fade

> animations. Subframes, same-doc and cross-origin server redirects are

> TODOs.

>

> We use a new hook OnDidNavigate() to observe the finishing of a request

> (committed successfully), and use DidFinishNavigation() to observe the

> non-committed requests (204/205/Download, replaced or cancelled). Using

> a new hook because the OnRenderWidgetHostViewSwapped() timing is too

> late [1].

>

> Edge cases:

> - Another navigation commits while the user is still swiping across the

> screen: synchronously destroy the impl_.

> - Another navigation cancels our navigation and our navigation isn't

> pending-commit. Play the cancel animation to bring back the active

> page.

> - Our navigation cancels other navigations. No action.

> - With NavigationQueuing, a previously pending navigation has committed

> before our navigation commits. No action.

> - Our navigation has committed (so the animation manager is displaying

> the invoke animation / waiting for the new renderer to submit a frame

> / displaying the cross-fade animation) while another navigation

> commits. This can happen while navigation queuing or with a client

> redirect. In this case we synchronously destroy the impl_.

>

> [1]: OnRenderWidgetHostViewSwapped happens during

> RFHManager::CommitPending, and CommitPending happens after

> WCI::DidNavigateMainFramePreCommit [2]. At

> DidNavigateMainFramePreCommit, we will reset the LocalSurfaceId on the

> old View. Because we need to clone the old View's visual state, the

> notification needs to be placed before the LocalSurfaceId is reset.

> [2]: https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:content/browser/renderer_host/navigator.cc;drc=d3dcc876aec63f37b5c9b38281e7485ff24b7bd3;l=511

entry.title: Shared Storage: Change to per-origin byte limit
entry.content:
To increase developer ergonomics, we drop the limit on number of

key-value pairs per origin, as well as the previous character limits

for keys and values. We move instead to a total byte quota for each

origin.



Note that, strictly speaking, there will still a key and value length

limit, in that each key and value must necessarily be less than or

equal to the quota, given that the total of all lengths of keys and

values must not exceed the quota.



We accomplish this by updating the previous feature param

`blink::features::kMaxSharedStorageEntriesPerOrigin` to a new

feature param `blink::features::kMaxSharedStorageBytesPerOrigin`,

deleting the previous feature param

`blink::features::kMaxSharedStorageStringLength`, and replacing

instances of the later with half of the new value for

`blink::features::kMaxSharedStorageBytesPerOrigin` (as we are

measuring the length in number of char16_t's).



For more information, see

https://github.com/WICG/shared-storage/pull/132.

entry.title: Read clipboard_paste_data in ClipboardHostImpl::Read* methods
entry.content:
This CL simplifies the callbacks in read methods of ClipboardHostImpl

to use the data found in `clipboard_paste_data` instead of a copy.

This is required by the Data Controls feature to allow tabs to paste

between each other using cached data instead of the OS clipboard.



To do so, a `Merge` method is added to `ClipboardPasteData` and the

caching logic in `ClipboardHostImpl` is tweaked to properly pass the

data for reads with the same seqno. This CL shouldn't change existing

behavior besides that.

entry.title: media/gpu/chromeos: Change VideoDecoderPipeline::OnFrameDecode interface
entry.content:
This modifies VideoDecoderPipeline::OnFrameDecoded() to accept a

FrameResource. OnFrameDecoded() was previously injected into the backends

via the OutputCb callback parameter in backend implementations of

VideoDecoder::Initialize(). To avoid changing VideoDecoder, a new

Initialize() interface was added to VideoDecoderMixin. Instead of

OutputCb, VideoDecoderMixin::Initialize() uses a VideoDecoderPipeline

specific callback, PipelineOutputCb. PipelineOutputCb accepts a

FrameResource as its argument. The inherited Initialize has a final

implementation to avoid confusion about what ChromeOS decoder backends

need to implement.



All of the decoder backends have been changed to use the new

Initialize() method. Since every decoder backend is VideoFrame-based,

they each simply wrap a decoded VideoFrame as a VideoFrameResource,

and send it to the new PipelineOutputCb callback.

entry.title: Fix applicable scope of Internals::setForcedColorsAndDarkPreferredColorScheme()
entry.content:
Previously the function had a local ColorSchemeHelper which resets

color scheme settings when it destructs, so the forced color flag

only applied to the UpdateAllLifecyclePhasesForTest() in the

function. This causes problems such as

1. If the test runs more document lifecycles (which may be arbitrary

depending on the scheduler or the test runner), the forced color

won't apply;

2. Composited scrollbars are not updated with the forced color because

they are repainted in cc after blink's BeginMainFrame-triggered

document lifecycle update.



Now store ColorSchemeHelper as an optional field of Internals. After

it's emplaced, it will destruct and restore color scheme settings

when the page unloads.



fast/forms/color-scheme/scrollbar/dynamic-color-scheme-change.html is

modified to include an explicit composited scrolling case, with

rebaselines. The old baseline contained wrong rendering of composited

scrollbars with wrong color schemes.

entry.title: Clean up kResetCheckDefaultBrowser since it is no longer used
entry.content:
This was used to trigger a one-time reprompt for users who had

previously declined the default browser prompt. At this point, all

existing users who aren't on a web app, in a test, or using a managed

pref have this value set to false so this will never be triggered.



New users would trigger this on the second browser load (there is

a check that the user isn't in the first run) but this reset happens

before the bar is shown for the first time so it resets an empty

value.



The only case where this could trigger for a user now would be if

someone dismissed the default browser prompt before 2016 and then has

had a managed pref since 2016 and now for some reason the pref is no

longer managed. This seems to be super rare and not worth keeping this

logic around for.

Introduces an in-script _LITERAL_SKIP_REGEX_STRINGS config to support

provide it each time (also error prone with human input).

entry.title: heap: Remove Blink's GCTaskRunner
entry.content:
Note: This change does not affect production semantics of garbage

collection.



Safepoint support was necessary in the initial implementation of

Oilpan (anno 2015) to run stack-less GCs in a timely fashion. The

safepoint mechanism uses task observers and as such hooks into _every_

task that was executed on the main thread. This completely bypassed

the scheduler and any heuristics it may have to meet deadlines.



These days the GCs are all triggered through unified heap in V8.

Asynchronous GCs (== stack-less GC) are implemented via scheduling

non-nestable tasks through `PostNonNestableTask()` for GC

finalizations.



The safepoint hook was still used to perform stack-less GCs after JS

`gc()` intrinsic calls in testing scenarios. These days these are

better written using `asyncGC()` (in web tests) and using the advanced

options for the `gc()` intrinsic that allow for awaitable async GC

otherwise (using `await gc({type: 'major', execution: 'async'})`).



A small side effect of this is that we also make prod faster by

removing a task observer that was otherwise always present.

entry.title: Remove non_network_url_loader_factory_remotes_
entry.content:
Previously, `NavigationURLLoaderImpl`

- Created all per-scheme `mojo::Remote` for known schemes in

`non_network_url_loader_factory_remotes_`, and then

- Created a `WeakWrapperSharedURLLoaderFactory` connecting to the

per-scheme `mojo::Remote` upon a request for the scheme.



This CL

- Creates a `SharedURLLoaderFactory` upon a request for the scheme,

- Caches and reuses it via `non_network_url_loader_factories_`, and

- Avoids creating per-scheme factories/Remotes unless actually used.

- Changes the name and signature of `ContentBrowserClient`'s

`RegisterNonNetworkNavigationURLLoaderFactories`

to `CreateNonNetworkNavigationURLLoaderFactory` to align with the

new factory creation model.



This is to

- Simplify the logic by always using `url_loader_factory::Create()`

and removing a `url_loader_factory::GetTestingInterceptor()` call.

- Simplify the lifetime.

Previously, `NavigationURLLoaderImpl::url_loader_` had a raw

reference to

`NavigationURLLoaderImpl::non_network_url_loader_factory_remotes_`

via `WeakWrapperSharedURLLoaderFactory`, and thus there was a

deconstruction order dependency between these two members.

This CL removes this dependency, and now

`GetOrCreateNonNetworkLoaderFactory()` and its returned factory

can be used without carefully considering the lifetime of

`NavigationURLLoaderImpl`.
